    "narrative": "For our April 18th slate, **Corbin Carroll** leads the charge with an elite 80.12 projection, bolstered by a prime spot in the #2 hole and a favorable matchup against Max Scherzer where his xwOBA upside remains a primary driver. **Tyler Soderstrom** and **James Wood** also grade out as high-floor, high-ceiling plays; **Soderstrom** benefits from a massive 19% SP skill advantage against Erick Fedde, while **Wood** leverages a leadoff assignment and a favorable matchup against Adrian Houser to hit the 71.32 mark. We are leaning heavily into speed-positive matchups today: **Brice Turang**, **Dalton Rushing**, and **Max Muncy** all receive critical efficiency bumps due to opposing battery pairings that are susceptible to the running game, helping them comfortably clear the 60-point \"Strong\" threshold despite some volatility in their lineup positions.\n\nThe most difficult decision on the morning was leaving **Seiya Suzuki** on the bench. With a score of 52.23, he fell just short of our rotation; while his base metrics remain solid, he is hampered by a difficult matchup against Freddy Peralta and a concerning BvP history, combined with a lower projected SP skill score. We opted to prioritize the high-upside plate appearances of **Jose Caballero** and **Mickey Moniak**, whose platoon advantages against their respective opponents provided a more favorable path to production.\n\nRisks remain elevated across the board as we await official lineup confirmation for nearly every slot. Specifically, our plays involving **Jazz Chisholm Jr.**, **Giancarlo Stanton**, and **Vinnie Pasquantino** are currently fighting an incoming wind factor, which provides a slight drag on their base projections. We will be monitoring the final batting orders closely; should **Luis Campusano** be moved further down or out of the order entirely, we have the flexibility to adjust, though his current score of 49.63 is already marginal enough that he serves as a pivot point for our daily game cap management.",
